Title : Harry Heath
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}
{{Use Australian English|date=February 2016}}
'''Henry Francis Trafford ("Harry") Heath''' (19 December 1885 – 9 September 1967) was an [[Australian (people)|Australian]] [[cricket]]er and [[clergyman]].

Born in [[Kadina, South Australia|Kadina]], [[South Australia]], Heath appeared in three [[first-class cricket|first-class matches]] for the [[Australian Imperial Force Touring XI]] and [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]] between 1919 and 1924 as a left-handed [[batting (cricket)|batsman]] who [[bowling (cricket)|bowled]] left-arm [[medium pace bowling|slow-medium pace]]. He scored 35 [[run (cricket)|runs]] with a highest score of 21 and took seven [[wicket]]s with a best performance of five for 43.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/16/16153/16153.html Harry Heath at ''CricketArchive'']</ref>

He served as a [[Methodist]] chaplain to the Australian armed forces in [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Chaplains: Appointments, Terminations, Etc.|journal=Commonwealth of Australia Gazette|date=21 February 1918|pages= 337–38|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/232463564/24997084|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> He married Irene Whellas Bain at the [[United Free Church|United Free Church of Scotland]] in [[Aberdeen]] on 12 September 1919.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Chaplains in WW1|url=http://ww1chaplains.gravesecrets.net/h.html|website=ww1chaplains.gravesecrets.net|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> They returned to South Australia in 1920, but a few years later they moved to Scotland, where he became a minister in the United Free Church in [[Edinburgh]] in 1926.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Rev. H. F. T. Heath|journal=Saturday Journal|date=20 February 1926|page= 14|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/199261793|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> He died in Edinburgh on 9 September 1967.

